{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0b6b74c7-a044-47ee-b964-7d54f51a7a10","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`**.\n\n- **`dotnet watch`** monitors your source files and automatically rebuilds/reruns when changes are detected. This is the hot reload mechanism in .NET.\n- **`dotnet test`** runs tests once and exits — no file watching.\n- **`dotnet run`** runs the app once and exits — no file watching.\n\nFor a test project like yours, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will re-run your tests automatically whenever you save a file change. For an app project you'd use `dotnet watch run`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a2e6cbd1-5bbd-415d-b2ca-29b665a53eae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to benefit from hot reload in .NET - whether they should use `dotnet test` or `dotnet run`. Let me look at the project files to understand the context better.","outputTokens":192,"requestId":"202D:343824:34CC764:3A90290:6A02EBC0"},"id":"ecae7a02-387b-4642-8a23-da684c4cff35","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:58:52.477Z","parentId":"0a562ecf-54df-413b-97db-f8877e49912f"}
